<dl id="n25197a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25197a">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25197a"> 197(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ld Uxbridge buries leg <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25197a"><li>FW 11.06 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n25197a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n25197a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25197a">MS Texas I.1-10</ms> </li><li>JJA Not reproduced <a name="ad3ydash" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad3ydash">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad3.htm#n25197a">Draft: I.1&sect;1.3</a>+'/2.3+' </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: The illustrious and valiant Earl Uxbridge, Lieutenant-General of His Britannic Majesty, Commander in Chief of the English, Belgian and Dutch cavalry, was wounded on the 18 June 1815 at the memorable battle of Waterloo, losing a leg to grape-shot. M. Hyacinthe Joseph-Marie Paris asked if he might bury the leg in his garden, later turning the place into a kind of reliquary shrine. Visitors were first taken to see the bloody chair upon which Uxbridge had sat during the amputation, before being escorted into the garden, where the leg had its own tombstone, </mm> </dd></dl>
